 Also — quickly on the Indian legal domain segregation you asked for, here's how I'd split the LoRA adapters:

  ┌──────────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │       Adapter        │                              Laws Covered                               │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Criminal             │ BNS, BNSS, BSA (new IPC/CrPC/Evidence Act)                              │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Civil Procedure      │ CPC, Limitation Act, Specific Relief Act                                │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Constitutional       │ Constitution, Fundamental Rights, Amendment jurisprudence               │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Corporate/Commercial │ Companies Act, Contract Act, NI Act, SEBI                               │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Family/Personal      │ Hindu Marriage Act, Muslim Personal Law, Succession Acts, POCSO, DV Act │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Property/Real Estate │ TPA, Registration Act, RERA, Land Acquisition                           │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Labour               │ Industrial Disputes Act, 4 Labour Codes, Factories Act                  │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Tax                  │ Income Tax Act, GST, Customs                                            │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ IP                   │ Patents, Copyright, Trademarks                                          │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Banking/Insolvency   │ RBI Act, SARFAESI, IBC                                                  │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Cyber/Data           │ IT Act 2000, DPDP Act 2023                                              │
  └──────────────────────┴─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  A single case can activate multiple adapters (e.g., a corporate fraud case needs Criminal + Corporate + Banking). The router handles
   multi-label classification, not just single-class.


can lora do this much fine tuning ?                                                                                                 
                                                                                                                                      
⏺ Great question — this is the most important technical clarification in the whole design. Honest answer: LoRA alone cannot do this.  
  But LoRA + PageIndex together can, because they split the job.                                                                      
                                                                                                                                      
  Here's the key insight most people miss:                                                                                            
                                                                                                                                      
  ---                                       
  What LoRA Actually Does (and Doesn't Do)
                                                                                                                                      
  LoRA injects small trainable matrices into the attention layers (~0.1–0.5% of total parameters). It adapts behaviour, it does not   
  store knowledge.                                                                                                                    
                                                                                                                                      
  ┌───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐   
  │                         What LoRA CAN do well                         │               What LoRA CANNOT do well                │
  ├───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤   
  │ Legal reasoning style and structure                                   │ Memorising 50,000 legal sections                      │   
  ├───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤   
  │ Understanding legal terminology (mens rea, locus standi, cognizable   │ Knowing exact BNS section numbers reliably            │   
  │ offence)                                                              │                                                       │   
  ├───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤   
  │ Formatting outputs as legal arguments / citations                     │ Recalling specific case judgments accurately          │   
  ├───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤   
  │ Interpreting a lawyer's query in legal context                        │ Cross-referencing "See Appendix G" or "Refer Section  │   
  │                                                                       │ 302"                                                  │   
  ├───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤   
  │ Classifying case domain (router)                                      │ Keeping up with law amendments post-training          │   
  ├───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤   
  │ Argument writing style                                                │ Injecting large entirely new factual knowledge        │   
  └───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘   
                                                                                                                                      
  The fundamental limit: LoRA with rank r=64 on a 7B model adds roughly 20–40MB of new weights. You cannot fit Indian legal knowledge 
  into 40MB. If you try, the model will confidently hallucinate section numbers, case names, and judgments — the worst possible       
  failure mode for a legal tool.                                                                                                      
                                                                                                                                      
  ---                                                                                                                                 
  How the Design Splits the Responsibility Correctly                                                                                  
                                                                                                                                      
  This is why the pipeline is designed the way it is:                                                                                 
                                                                                                                                      
  LoRA = Legal Intelligence       PageIndex = Legal Knowledge                                                                         
  ─────────────────────────       ─────────────────────────                                                                           
  How to think legally            What the law actually says                                                                      
  How to write arguments          Exact BNS/BNSS section text                                                                         
  How to structure legal Q&A      Real case judgment content                                                                          
  Understand "what is mens rea"   Find which sections apply to this case                                                              
  Classify criminal vs civil      Retrieve Section 103 BNS verbatim                                                                   
  Argument writing style          Cross-reference "See Appendix G"                                                                    
                                                                                                                                      
  Neither works alone:                                                                                                                
  - LoRA without PageIndex = smart legal writer who hallucinated their bar exam                                                       
  - PageIndex without LoRA = dumb retriever that finds text but can't reason about it like a lawyer                                   
                                                                                                                                      
  Together: PageIndex fetches ground truth, LoRA knows what to do with it.                                                            
                                                                                                                                      
  ---                                                                                                                                 
  Specific Concerns About This Pipeline                                                                                               
                                                                                                                                      
  1. Multi-adapter composition (set_adapter(["criminal", "constitutional"]))                                                          
                                                                                                                                      
  This works but degrades slightly when adapters are trained on overlapping or conflicting data. Research shows ~3-8% accuracy drop vs
   single adapter. Mitigation: train adapters on clean, non-overlapping domain data. Criminal + Argument-gen works great              
  (complementary tasks). Criminal + Civil might interfere.                                                                            
                                                                                                                                      
  Recommendation: Test single adapter vs composed adapters on InLegalBench. If composition degrades > 5%, use a single "merged"       
  adapter for common combinations instead.                                                                                            
                                                                                                                                      
  2. BNS/BNSS Knowledge Gap                                                                                                           
                                                                                                                                      
  Qwen2.5-7B's training cutoff is late 2024. BNS/BNSS/BSA were passed in 2023 and operationalised in 2024 — they may be partially in  
  the base model's training data. But exact section numbers, wording, and cross-references should NEVER be trusted from LoRA memory   
  alone. PageIndex is the ground truth for all section content. LoRA just helps the model understand the domain.                      
                                                                                                                                      
  3. Dataset Size (1,500–5,000 pairs)                                                                                                 
                                                                                                                                      
  For knowledge memorisation — too small.                                                                                             
  For behaviour adaptation — sufficient.                                                                                              
                                                                                                                                      
  Since we're using LoRA for behaviour (not knowledge), 3,000–5,000 good quality pairs per domain is actually enough. Quality matters 
  far more than quantity here. 500 expert-reviewed pairs beat 5,000 noisy scraped ones.                                               
                                                                                                                                  
  4. Argument Generation Specifically                                                                                                 
                                                                                                                                      
  This is where LoRA's limits show most. A 7B model with LoRA will not generate courtroom-quality arguments from scratch. This is why 
  the design routes argument generation to the big model API (GPT-4.1/Claude) — the LoRA small model only prepares the structured     
  legal brief (Stage 1). The big model does the actual argument writing (Stage 2).                                                    
                                                                                                                                      
  The lora-argument-gen adapter on the small model is about: formatting legal briefs correctly, knowing what a "structured brief"     
  looks like, extracting the right facts from case context. Not about writing the final argument.                                     
                                                                                                                                      
  ---                                                                                                                                 
  Should You Use Anything Besides LoRA?                                                                                               
                                                                                                                                      
  For this pipeline, two additions worth considering:                                                                                 
                                                                                                                                      
  RAG-only baseline first (no LoRA): Before training any adapter, test PageIndex + base model + good system prompt. You might get     
  70-80% of the quality at 0% of the training cost. LoRA then becomes an incremental improvement, not a foundation.                   
                                                                                                                                      
  Larger LoRA rank for argument adapter: Standard rank is r=8 to r=64. For the argument generation task adapter, go r=128 or r=256.
  This is the one place where you need more capacity — legal writing style is complex.
                                                                                                                                      
  ---                                                                                                                                 
  Bottom line for your pipeline:                                                                                                      
                                                                                                                                      
  The design is sound precisely because LoRA is not being asked to be the knowledge store. PageIndex carries the legal knowledge. LoRA
   carries the legal intelligence. The only adjustment I'd recommend: test zero-shot (no LoRA) first so you know what you're actually 
  gaining from the fine-tuning effort before committing 6 weeks of data prep.                                                         
                                                                                                                                      
